context: To the east of the county are <b8_0>upland areas leading to the Pennines<b8_0/>. <a4_0>North of the Ribble<a4_0/> is <b5_0>Beacon Fell Country Park<b5_0/> and the Forest of Bowland, another AONB. Much of the lowland in this area is devoted to <a0_0><b6_0>dairy farming<b6_0/> and <b7_0>cheesemaking<b7_0/><a0_0/>, whereas the higher ground is more suitable for <a1_0><b9_0>sheep<b9_0/><a1_0/>, and the highest ground is <a2_0>uncultivated moorland<a2_0/>. The valleys of the River Ribble and its tributary the Calder form a large gap to the west of the Pennines, overlooked by Pendle Hill. Most of the larger Lancashire towns are in these valleys South of the Ribble are the West Pennine Moors and the Forest of Rossendale where former cotton mill towns are in deep valleys. The Lancashire Coalfield, largely in <a3_0>modern-day Greater Manchester<a3_0/>, extended into Merseyside and to Ormskirk, Chorley, Burnley and Colne in Lancashire.
